@bbejeck After thinking a bit more about it I think there is still a small risk, because a separate consumer being able to consume the message (meaning that the consumer has discovered the topic and hence being able to fetch from it) does not necessarily mean that the streams' embedded consumer, which is independent, would be able to discover the new topic in time as well. Though adding this one more line does reduce the timing issue by a lot. 

So I think a safer fix would be 0) do not close Streams right after producing the data, 1) use `TestUtils.waitForCondition` to continuously check that `stateStoreToSourceTopic = builder.stateStoreNameToSourceTopics()`, until say 30 seconds has elapsed and then report the test as failed. 2) call `streams.close()` in a finally block.

WDYT?

@umesh9794 I believe you can also hit ``request.timeout.ms`` and get an IOException here https://github.com/umesh9794/kafka/blob/f2b35a8e56d83301a42a09fef61a9ba752acce70/core/src/main/scala/kafka/server/KafkaServer.scala#L446

Also there is another place this is getting logged here that could be fixed:
https://github.com/umesh9794/kafka/blob/f2b35a8e56d83301a42a09fef61a9ba752acce70/core/src/main/scala/kafka/server/KafkaServer.scala#L535

@ijuma do you see any other possible socket timeouts that can get hit here?
